    def generate_medium_tasks(self):
        return [
        "Build a small, dependency-light ETL module that runs entirely in memory and demonstrates a cloud-ready design around Azure Blob Storage semantics. Generate a reproducible synthetic order stream (seeded RNG) with fields {orderId, userId, ts, items, subtotal}. Implement: (1) schema validation with explicit type/required checks; (2) an enrichment pass that computes tax, total, and a boolean flag for suspicious negative/zero subtotals; (3) a partitioning strategy function that maps each record to the path shape you would use in object storage (e.g., container/raw/day=YYYY-MM-DD/hour=HH)—return these path strings as data, do not write anything; and (4) an in-memory manifest (list[dict]) summarizing per-partition counts and min/max timestamps. Consult the official Azure Blob SDK guidance on retries/metadata and place a two-to-three sentence digest in a module docstring string you return. Final return should be a single Python dict: {'sampleRecords': first 10, 'partitions': sorted unique partition keys, 'manifest': list of {partition, count, minTs, maxTs}, 'docNotes': the digest}. No files, no network calls—just clean code, clear data structures, and printed debug lines that would be useful if later containerized.",
        
        "Create a config-driven in-memory pipeline that simulates preparing documents for Azure AI Search. Fabricate 50 support tickets with fields {id, createdAt, product, text}. Implement normalization (lowercasing, trimming, NFC normalization), a simple tokenizer/term count, and construction of indexable docs with the following shape: id (key), createdAt (datetime string), product (filterable/facetable), text (searchable), terms (collection of strings). Add a function that, given a query string and optional product filter, shows which fields would be considered and returns a mock ranked list by term overlap (ties broken by recency). Skim the official field/analyzer guidance and include a short justification in plain language as a string. Return {'indexDocs': first 5 docs, 'fieldDesign': {name: {type, searchable, filterable, facetable, retrievable}}, 'searchDemo': sample results for two queries, 'docNotes': your analyzer/field rationale}. Keep everything deterministic with a fixed seed and produce straightforward, easily testable helpers.",
        
        "Implement a compact change-data-capture simulator reflecting Azure Cosmos DB patterns. In memory, generate a base collection (≈30 docs) and a delta feed (≈10 ops) with items shaped as {op in ['insert','update','delete'], id, userId (partitionKey), body}. Build: (1) a validator that enforces presence and stability of the partition key; (2) an RU budget estimator using a simple per-operation table you define (e.g., insert>update>delete), aggregated over the delta; and (3) a deterministic replay plan that produces exactly-once final state when re-applied. Also produce a synthetic “change feed envelope” list showing logical sequence numbers and partition key ranges to illustrate ordering guarantees. Read the high-level docs for consistency and change feed; place a three-bullet digest (string) explaining eventual vs session consistency trade-offs and consumer ordering expectations. Return {'finalCollection': first 8 docs post-replay, 'feedEnvelopes': first 8 envelopes, 'ruEstimate': number, 'assumptions': digest}. Focus on correctness of merge semantics and idempotency, not I/O.",
        
        "Design an in-memory messaging flow that mirrors Azure Service Bus topic/subscription patterns for an analytics ETL completion signal. Synthesize a small set of batch summaries shaped {batchId, partition, rowCount, checksum, status}. Create a publisher that emits a normalized message dict with stable identifiers and a de-duplication key. Create three consumer roles—'metrics-writer', 'alerting', and 'catalog-updater'—each represented by a handler function that decides to ack, retry, or dead-letter based on message content (simulate retries with a counter). Add a simple backoff algorithm for retries and a dead-letter policy (e.g., >2 failures). Return a single object: {'published': first 5 messages, 'routing': mapping of subscription→received ids, 'retries': timeline of attempts, 'deadLetters': list of parked ids, 'designNotes': short prose on de-dup keys, idempotent sinks, and poison-message isolation}. Consult official conceptual docs for topics/subscriptions and summarize two key constraints (e.g., max size implications, ordering caveats) in designNotes. No files, no queues—just pure functions and lists.",
        
        "Construct a lightweight telemetry aggregator that models Azure Event Hubs partitions and checkpointing—purely in memory. Generate 500 synthetic telemetry records {deviceId, ts, cpu}, assign each to a partition via a hash(deviceId) mod P (choose P=4), and simulate consumption by two consumer groups. Implement a checkpoint structure {consumerGroup, partitionId, offset} and a read loop that processes records in order, updating checkpoints and supporting restart from the last saved offset. Add a tiny windowed aggregator that produces per-partition p50/p95 CPU for 5-minute windows (mock windows defined over your ts). Return {'partitions': stats per partition, 'checkpoints': final checkpoint table, 'windowAgg': sample aggregates, 'opsNotes': short text on partitioning keys and consumer-group isolation}. Skim the Event Hubs docs to capture a two-sentence note about throughput units vs partitions and why checkpointing reduces duplicate processing work. Keep logic deterministic and testable; no external systems, no files.",
        
        "Assemble a miniature in-memory packaging of a model for an Azure Machine Learning-style workflow. Generate synthetic binary-classification data, split deterministically, train a very small model (e.g., logistic regression implemented with a library or a hand-crafted sigmoid with gradient steps), and compute metrics (accuracy, precision, recall, f1). Define an 'evaluation bundle' object with keys: codeVersion (string), dataHash (placeholder), metrics (dict), artifacts (references to objects in memory like coefficients), and an interface spec: input schema (feature names/types) and output schema (probability, label). Add a 'promotion gate' function that returns a PASS/FAIL decision based on configurable thresholds and drift sanity checks (compare mean feature vector of train vs test). Return {'bundle': summary dict, 'samplePredictions': first 10 with probs, 'gateDecision': struct with reasons}. Read the high-level registry/endpoint concepts and distill two sentences on why stable input/output contracts reduce deployment risk.",
        
        "Model an external-table ingestion plan like Azure Synapse would expect—without writing anything. Start with an in-memory schema for orders {orderId:int, userId:int, ts:datetime string, total:float, currency:str}. Implement a type-mapping function from this logical schema to SQL column definitions, adding nullable rules and default values. Generate 100 synthetic rows and validate conformance, collecting any type-coercion warnings. Produce a 'COPY-readiness' planner that decides file layout hints (row group sizes, partition columns day/hour, escape/quote policy) as data, not files. Return {'sqlSchema': list of column defs, 'coercionWarnings': list, 'partitionsPlanned': list of hypothetical paths, 'copyHints': dict of settings}. Review the Synapse external table and COPY conceptual docs and capture two sentences in a 'notes' string about common pitfalls (e.g., quoting, UTF-8, CRLF). The aim is to show design clarity and validation discipline, not execution.",
        
        "Create an ADLS-style partitioning and lifecycle planner in memory. Generate synthetic event data {userId, ts, eventType} and propose a hierarchical namespace layout (e.g., zone=raw|curated, date partitions, and optional bucketing by user hash). Implement: (1) a function that maps records to idealized paths; (2) a small 'lifecycle adviser' that tags partitions as hot/warm/cold based on recency; and (3) a compliance checker that verifies that a given partition list matches expected conventions (no empty directories, consistent depth). Return {'pathPlan': first 12 path strings, 'lifecycle': per-partition tier suggestions, 'conformance': list of {partition, ok, issues}, 'guidance': a short paragraph on hierarchical namespace benefits}. Reference the ADLS hierarchical namespace concept in your guidance and emphasize why predictable layouts make cost and access simpler.",
        
        "Design a Key Vault-aware configuration facade entirely in memory. Define a logical application config that includes non-secret values (e.g., retry counts, feature flags) and secret placeholders (e.g., 'kv://payments/PRIMARY_KEY'). Implement: (1) a resolver that returns a merged config in which secrets are represented by opaque tokens (never real secrets); (2) a rotation planner that, given 'v1'→'v2' for a secret name, produces a safe rollout sequence with dual-read period and cutover marker; and (3) a linter that flags config keys that appear to embed secrets directly. Return {'resolvedConfig': dict with placeholders intact, 'rotationPlan': ordered steps, 'lintFindings': issues list, 'notes': two-sentence explanation of why indirection + rotation windows reduce outages}. Mention Key Vault secret naming and versioning conventions at a high level in notes; no actual secret access.",
        
        "Specify a small REST surface for a prediction microservice intended for Azure Container Apps, and exercise it in memory. Define endpoints: GET /health (returns {'status','version'}), POST /predict (accepts a JSON object with typed features, returns {'proba','label','modelVersion','latencyMs'}), and GET /ready (simulates warmup state). Implement input validation (types, required features, range checks), consistent error responses, and a simple latency sampler around predict(). Build a 'contract tester' that runs a suite of sample requests (valid, missing fields, out-of-range) and summarizes pass/fail with reasons. Return {'openApiSketch': a minimal structure, 'samples': list of request→response dicts, 'contractReport': aggregate verdict, 'opsNotes': short text on readiness vs liveness probes and why version is echoed}. Keep it framework-agnostic and zero-I/O.",
        
        "Develop a tiny, extensible data-quality engine in memory. Accept a schema spec (columns, types, required) and a rule set (e.g., amount >= 0, status ∈ {'NEW','PAID','VOID'}, ts not null). Generate synthetic rows with deliberate issues, run the engine, and produce a structured result with per-rule pass/fail counts and first N offending examples. Include a 'severity' notion (ERROR vs WARN) that drives an overall gate decision. Add a 'profile' pass that computes completeness/uniqueness per column to contextualize failures. Return {'rulesEvaluated': list with counts, 'violations': dict of rule→examples, 'profile': dict of basic stats, 'gate': {'decision','reasons'}}. Include a short note on how these results would feed monitoring or a catalog entry. Emphasize clear, testable rule evaluation and deterministic synthetic inputs.",
        
        "Create an exploratory data analysis routine focused on drift watch-listing—no files, all in memory. Generate two small synthetic datasets representing 'current' and 'reference' windows with overlapping schemas. Compute per-feature summary stats (mean, std, min, max) for numeric and frequency tables for categoricals. Implement a simple drift decision using KS for numeric and population stability index (PSI) for categoricals, and produce slice examples where drift is most pronounced. Return {'summaryRef': stats, 'summaryCur': stats, 'driftFindings': list of {feature, test, score, flag}, 'watchlist': top 3 features to monitor with suggested thresholds}. Add a brief rationale string on threshold selection (e.g., 'KS>0.1 as early warning') and how this would connect to an alerting pipeline. Keep all randomness seeded.",
        
        "Sketch a miniature feature-store pattern entirely in memory. Starting from synthetic transactions {userId, ts, amount, channel}, define point-in-time safe features per user: rolling 7-day sum, txn count, average ticket size, and one-hot channel frequencies. Build a 'feature registry' dict that lists feature names, owners, and freshness SLAs. Implement a retrieval function that, given userId and a cutoff timestamp, returns a consistent feature vector computed only from records ≤ cutoff. Return {'registry': registry dict, 'exampleVectors': first 5 users at a given cutoff, 'freshnessReport': list of feature→max age, 'notes': a short explanation of avoiding label leakage}. The goal is to demonstrate point-in-time correctness and basic governance concepts without storage or network.",
        
        "Author a reconciliation engine that compares a hypothetical 'source' and 'sink' view—in memory only. Synthesize two datasets with intentional mismatches (missing rows, duplicate keys, tiny numeric deltas). Compute row-level parity by key, aggregate counts of missing/extra/changed rows, and produce a concise decision object indicating whether differences are within tolerance. Add a pluggable tolerance model: absolute, relative %, and per-column custom thresholds. Return {'parity': {'missing':…, 'extra':…, 'changed':…}, 'tolerance': config you used, 'decision': {'status','reasons'}, 'examples': small samples of each issue}. Include a short operator-centric note on next steps (e.g., replays for missing, tombstones for extra, and numeric rounding policies). No I/O, just clean algorithms and objects.",
        
        "Implement a tiny pipeline-orchestration state machine in memory. Define tasks (extract, transform, validate, publish) with deterministic durations and failure probabilities (seeded). Simulate a run that emits state transitions with timestamps, supports retries with exponential backoff, and halts on a 'validate' hard failure. Calculate critical-path timing and produce a 'run summary' structure capturing step durations, retries, and final outcome. Return {'timeline': ordered list of transitions, 'criticalPathMs': number, 'retries': per-step counts, 'summary': object with totals}. Add a concise engineering note on idempotency (why 'publish' must be idempotent if retried) and on where you would surface health probes. You are modeling control flow only—no threads, files, or external APIs.",
        
        "Build an SLO modeling module for latency, tailored to an analytics API—purely in memory. Generate synthetic latency samples per endpoint, compute p50/p90/p95 and error rate, and compare against SLO targets read from a small configuration dict. Produce an 'SLO decision' per endpoint (MEETS/AT-RISK/VIOLATES) with reasons, plus a projection that shows how many ms you must shave off p95 to meet targets. Add a simple 'budget burn' notion (percent of error budget consumed in a window). Return {'summaries': per-endpoint stats, 'decisions': list of endpoint→status/reasons, 'projections': required improvements, 'notes': a short explanation of why p95 is generally preferred over mean}. Keep computations straightforward and deterministic.",
        
        "Prototype an analyzer for search relevance settings reminiscent of Azure AI Search—no external calls. Generate a small catalog of items with titles/descriptions and a few query strings. Implement BM25-style scoring in simplified form, then add a synonym expansion step (a dict mapping terms to sets) and an analyzer choice (e.g., lowercase + stemming flag). Compare baseline vs expanded scoring for each query and produce side-by-side ranked lists. Return {'queries': list, 'rankingsBaseline': dict, 'rankingsExpanded': dict, 'analysisNotes': 2–3 observations about recall/precision trade-offs}. The aim is to demonstrate how synonym maps and analyzer tweaks can shift ranking without wiring any backend. Keep all tokenization decisions explicit so results are explainable.",
        
        "Create a partition-design evaluator as if you were planning an Azure Cosmos DB container—entirely in memory. Given synthetic documents {userId, region, ts, payloadSize}, score three candidate partition keys: '/userId', '/region', and '/day' (derived). For each candidate, compute estimated cardinality, skew (top-k key %), and cross-partition query likelihood for common query shapes (by user, by region, by day). Return {'candidates': list of key→scores, 'bestKey': chosen path with justification, 'skewExamples': a few heavy keys, 'docNotes': brief text on RU cost trade-offs}. This is a design exercise: no containers, no queries—just back-of-the-envelope scoring with transparent assumptions and a deterministic seed.",
        
        "Write a miniature A/B analysis toolkit that operates on fully synthetic event streams—no files. Generate two variants with events {userId, ts, converted:0/1, revenue}. Compute conversion rate, average revenue per user, and uplift with a simple confidence interval (normal approximation is fine at this scale). Include a guardrail metric (e.g., error rate) and fail the test if guardrail regresses beyond a threshold. Provide a 'decision' object (SHIP/INVESTIGATE/STOP) with reasons and a sensitivity table showing how many additional conversions would change the decision. Return {'summary': per-variant metrics, 'uplift': estimate + CI, 'guardrails': status, 'decision': object, 'whatIf': small sensitivity results}. Keep the math and code clear, deterministic, and reviewable.",
        
        "Build a privacy-and-security preflight scanner that runs on in-memory synthetic rows. Implement regex-based detectors for emails, phone numbers, and obvious secret tokens; add a simple entropy-based heuristic for suspicious keys in config-like dicts. Run the scanner on synthetic data that deliberately includes a few issues and produce a structured finding set that groups by category and severity with counts and example snippets (redacted where appropriate). Add a 'policy advisor' that suggests whether each category should be blocked, masked, or allowed with logging. Return {'findings': list of {category, severity, count, examples}, 'policy': list of recommendations, 'gate': {'decision','reasons'}}. Include a brief note on false positives and how a Key Vault-style indirection mitigates accidental leakage. Everything remains in memory, deterministic, and testable.",
    ]
    def generate_medium_easy_tasks(self):
        return [
    """Engineer an in-memory batch ingestor that simulates Azure Service Bus semantics for a single topic with three independent subscriptions. Start by defining a deterministic generator that emits synthetic inventory adjustments (create/update/adjust) with fields: messageId (UUID but seeded), partitionKey (SKU), enqueueTime (monotonic), and a payload checksum. Implement at-least-once delivery using duplicate detection keyed by messageId within a sliding time window. Add a simple lock/settle model: when a subscriber pulls a batch, mark messages invisible for a configurable lock duration; acknowledgements settle them, expirations return them to the queue. Route accepted events to three subscribers: (1) metrics (per-SKU counts, moving receive age, and per-minute throughput), (2) reconciliation (idempotent application to produce final per-SKU quantity), and (3) alerts (flag negative inventory, impossible adjustments, or out-of-order timestamps). Each subscription has its own dead-letter queue after N consecutive failures with reason codes captured. Provide controls to vary batch size, lock duration, and dead-letter threshold at runtime and print a run summary: total enqueued, deduped, delivered, settled, redelivered, and dead-lettered; per-subscription lag timeline; and five sample routed records annotated with subscriber outcomes. Include a short documentation digest (2–4 sentences) on ordering scope (partitionKey level), lock duration vs processing time, and why idempotent writes are essential under redelivery. Acceptance: replaying the same seed yields identical end-state and metrics aside from explicit idempotency counters; artificially inflating processing time above lock duration measurably increases redeliveries without corrupting end-state; duplicate messageIds never change the reconciliation state more than once. Keep the interfaces clean—Producer, Broker, Subscriber—so you can swap retry/backoff policies without changing business logic. """,

    """Build a lightweight Event Hubs partitioning model to reason about hot partitions, consumer lag, and checkpointing behavior under restarts. Generate 2,000 synthetic device metrics across ~200 deviceIds with a stable deviceId→partition hash over 8 partitions. Enforce producer ordering per partition and introduce a per-partition append cap to emulate capacity units; when exceeded, drop events and record dropped counts. Simulate two consumer groups (“analytics” and “monitoring”) with configurable parallelism and maintain per-partition offsets and watermarks. Consumers pull in batches, apply simple transformation (e.g., derive moving average), and checkpoint after each batch. Implement restart of the analytics group mid-stream and demonstrate recovery from durable checkpoints with bounded reprocessing. Print a diagnostic report: per-partition message counts, skew (Gini or top-K share), consumer lag time-series, effective throughput per partition, drops, and a restart summary showing last checkpoint vs first post-restart read. Add a concise doc digest contrasting partitions (ordering/parallelism unit) with capacity (throughput units) and explain why checkpoint granularity trades reprocessing for recovery speed. Acceptance: with production ≤ consumption, lag trends toward zero; increasing consumer parallelism reduces lag without violating partition ordering; after restart, duplicates are limited to the last uncommitted batch by design. Keep all randomness seeded for reproducibility and allow toggling partition count to illustrate skew and scaling behavior.""",

    """Design a hierarchical layout planner for Azure Data Lake Storage Gen2 that organizes synthetic user activity events into governance-friendly paths while estimating lifecycle costs. Given deterministic events (userId, eventType, ts), map each record to lowercase, key=value path segments such as /zone=raw/date=YYYY-MM-DD/hour=HH/userBucket=NN/part-XXXX.json where userBucket=hash(userId)%100. Enforce invariants: fixed segment order, bounded directory depth, and strictly lowercase names. Classify data into hot/warm/cold tiers with simple recency rules (≤7 days hot, ≤60 warm, older cold) and produce an estimated monthly cost table using configurable per-GB storage and access assumptions plus read amplification for typical queries (DAU and events-by-type). Simulate a week of data and demonstrate partition pruning: queries constrained to a date filter should only scan matching directories; show the ratio of scanned-to-total files. Output: sample planned paths, tier assignments, projected costs by tier, and a governance note on atomic directory renames for backfills and using ACLs at folder boundaries. Add a validator that rejects illegal paths (wrong case, missing key segment, extra nesting) and proposes corrections. Acceptance: bucket distribution across userBucket is balanced (no bucket exceeds, say, 2× median count); lifecycle moves keep content-addressable checksums stable (report pre/post hashes); partition pruning demonstrably reduces scanned files when filtering by date or hour. Keep the planner deterministic and side-effect free, printing recommendations instead of touching any real storage.""",

    """Specify and validate a minimal scoring API intended to sit behind an API gateway for online inference. Define two endpoints: GET /health (returns build info and a synthetic dependency check) and POST /predict (accepts {requestId, timestamp, features:{...}} with strict types and bounds). Implement layered validation: schema typing, required fields, numeric bounds, categorical whitelist, and payload size limits. Standardize error envelopes with fields {code, field, message, hint} and make all failures deterministic and reproducible. Wrap predict() with latency sampling; send a fixed set of valid and invalid synthetic requests through and compute p50/p95 latency and error rate. Produce a compact test matrix with edge cases (missing features, wrong types, out-of-range, oversized), run it, and print the first failure per case. Output the final schema (as data), validation report, latency percentiles, and a short policy digest on rate limits per API key, header-based JWT checks, and caching rules (cacheable GET only). Acceptance: identical inputs yield identical outputs; invalid requests never reach the scoring core; and two consecutive runs with the same seed produce stable latency percentiles within small tolerance. Add a small step-load experiment (10→25→50 rps synthetic) to illustrate p95 growth while p50 remains flatter, and recommend a p95 SLO grounded in the results. Version the contract and include deprecation guidance with a target removal date for old fields.""",

    """Model a Key Vault–style configuration facade that enables safe, observable secret rotation without exposing raw values. Accept application configs that reference logical secret URIs like secret://payments-db/connStr?v=1. Provide a pluggable provider (simulated, deterministic) that resolves logical URIs to concrete values, caching entries with per-secret TTLs. Implement version-aware reads: during rotation windows, attempt v2 first then fallback to v1 while emitting structured events recording which version served each call. Add a linter that scans raw configs for high-entropy literals, forbidden substrings (e.g., “password=”), and potential environment-variable leaks; rank by severity and generate remediation hints. Simulate a rotation: stage v2 for two secrets, send read traffic with varying TTLs, complete cutover, then retire v1; verify zero “missing secret” incidents. Outputs: effective config (placeholders only), rotation timeline with served-version percentages, cache hit/miss metrics, and lint findings by severity. Provide an operational note explaining soft-delete and purge protection and why recovery windows matter. Acceptance: rotation never alters functional outcomes for callers; cache respects TTLs and picks up new versions within bounded time; linter flags embedded literals with minimal false positives. Design clean interfaces so future providers (HSM-backed keys, certificates) can be added without changing callers.""",

    """Implement a Cosmos DB–like change feed simulator to explore idempotent downstream processing and continuation tokens. Start from seeded base documents (id, partitionKey, etag, payload) and generate a time-ordered stream of insert/update/delete operations with logical sequence numbers (LSNs) per partition plus a global timestamp. Emit continuation tokens encoding (partition, LSN) positions; allow consumers to start from beginning, now, or a saved token. Enforce partition-key stability and produce tombstones on deletes that remain visible for a retention window. Build a consumer that applies operations idempotently to an in-memory sink, keeps per-document version histories, and persists the last continuation token. Provide an RU charge proxy: charge per operation by type/size, aggregate per partition, and report hot-partition penalties. Outputs: feed slices by partition, consumer checkpoints, final sink snapshot, RU proxy summaries, and a short operator note on backpressure when consumers lag (smaller batches reduce tail latency but increase RU/record). Acceptance: replaying the exact stream yields identical end state; out-of-order reads across partitions still maintain per-partition ordering; and expired tombstones disappear beyond retention. Keep seeds fixed for repeatable evaluation and expose a knob to vary batch size to observe throughput/latency tradeoffs.""",

    """Draft a compact design for an Azure AI Search–style index over synthetic product documents and run a tiny relevance experiment. Define a schema with a stable key, filterable fields (brand, createdDate), sortable fields (price, rating), and searchable text (name, description). Choose analyzers/tokenizers for English text and add a small synonym map (e.g., “tv, television; lappy, laptop”). Implement a naive TF–IDF scorer with optional synonym expansion and compute NDCG@5 for three representative queries under two configurations: baseline and synonym-augmented. Add faceting on brand and priceBucket, and demonstrate facet counts for “4k tv.” Validate that sortable and filterable fields are not full-text analyzed to preserve exact matching and sorting correctness. Outputs: index schema (as data), top-5 results with scores for three queries, NDCG deltas between configurations, example facet payloads, and a short design note on key immutability, incremental updates vs merges, and analyzer consistency between indexing and search. Acceptance: synonym expansion improves at least one query’s ranking without materially degrading others; faceting and filters behave deterministically; paging uses a stable order via tiebreakers. Keep randomness seeded to allow side-by-side comparisons when toggling synonyms or changing analyzer settings.""",

    """Assemble a retry/backoff policy model for a queue processor balancing throughput, fairness, and error containment. Generate a deterministic mixture of jobs (light/medium/heavy) with class-specific service times and transient error probabilities. Guard concurrency with a token-bucket cap and per-class weights to prevent starvation. On transient failures, apply exponential backoff with full jitter; on hard validation errors, dead-letter immediately with a reason code. Track visibility timeouts to emulate leases; jobs that overrun leases redeliver after timeout unless acknowledged. Produce dashboards as printed summaries: throughput per class, p95 latency, average attempts to success, retry histograms, and dead-letter reasons. Provide a fairness view: admitted share vs offered load and effective share under backpressure. Outputs: per-class metrics, tail latency evolution under increasing offered load, and a concise operator note on sizing visibility timeouts relative to p95 service time and why jitter reduces synchronized retry storms. Acceptance: with fixed seed, results are reproducible; increasing concurrency improves throughput until queueing elevates tail latency; lowering the dead-letter threshold reduces time-to-recovery for poison messages without harming genuine transient recoveries. Keep knobs (concurrency, weights, backoff) adjustable at runtime to observe tradeoffs.""",

    """Create a small data-quality gate for synthetic financial transactions that blocks bad data before analytics. Define a strict schema (id, ts, currencyCode, amount ≥ 0, channel) and implement rule families: schema/type validation, required field completeness, domain checks (ISO currency subset), referential sanity (id uniqueness within a sliding window), and lightweight consistency (non-negative daily sum, no future timestamps). Assign severities (BLOCK/WARN/INFO) and compute a final decision (PASS/WARN/BLOCK). Emit per-rule violation counts and top-N offending records with human-readable reasons and remediation hints. Add a compact column profile (completeness, uniqueness, min/max, top-K categories) to ground the decision. Outputs: gate decision, violation ledger, and column profiles, plus a brief integration hint on exporting counts as custom metrics for dashboards and alerts. Acceptance: replaying the same seed yields identical decisions; tightening domain lists predictably increases violations; injecting an out-of-range amount flips the decision from PASS to BLOCK. Keep the gate composable so new checks (regex on reference keys, cross-record balance assertions) can be toggled without restructuring the pipeline; ensure performance is deterministic by fixing batch sizes and seeds.""",

    """Engineer a point-in-time feature retrieval helper that prevents temporal leakage for downstream scoring. From deterministic synthetic transactions (userId, ts, amount, channel), compute features at a caller-supplied cutoff time: rolling 1/7/30-day spend sums and counts, average ticket, distinct channels in 7 days, and recency of last transaction. Enforce window boundaries that exclude events strictly after cutoff. Provide an interface that atomically returns features and a provenance note indicating the latest event included. Implement a tiny logistic scorer with fixed coefficients to yield a probability per (userId, cutoff). Demonstrate ten example predictions and show leakage-proof behavior by comparing features at T1<T2: cumulative features should not include events after T1. Outputs: feature definitions with window math, sample feature rows, predicted probabilities, and a “leakage proof” table illustrating monotonic relationships. Include a brief ownership/SLA note: freshness target (e.g., up to T−5 minutes), availability, and compatibility guarantees when adding a column. Acceptance: features computed at earlier cutoffs never include late events; predictions are deterministic across runs; requesting a cutoff earlier than the first event yields well-defined zeros/null-safe defaults without exceptions. Seed all randomness and keep computation purely in-memory to ensure repeatable results without external dependencies.""",

    """Prototype a circuit-breaker and bulkhead pattern for downstream dependencies typical of API Management backends. Create synthetic downstreams: payments (fast, occasional spikes), catalog (steady), and profile (slow tail). For each, track rolling error/latency windows and trip a circuit when consecutive failures or p95 latency exceed thresholds; implement half-open probing with limited concurrency before closing. Add bulkheads by limiting concurrent calls per dependency and queueing above limits with bounded wait; requests exceeding wait time fail fast with a clear reason. Build a small routing layer that fans out to dependencies per request and aggregates responses; on circuit open, return partial results with degraded-mode annotations. Outputs: time series of circuit states, rejected vs admitted counts per bulkhead, end-to-end p50/p95, and a degraded-mode sample response. Include a brief operations digest on tuning thresholds and the risks of synchronized reopen storms without jitter. Acceptance: with seeded spikes, circuits trip and recover as designed; bulkheads isolate slow profile from starving payments and catalog; degraded responses are explicit and consistent. Keep behavior deterministic and configurable at runtime to explore sensitivity.""",

    """Simulate Azure Functions–style orchestrations (Durable Functions concepts) using in-memory activities and a replayable event history. Model an orchestrator that coordinates three activities: validate, enrich, and persist for synthetic orders. Record a deterministic event history (scheduled, started, completed) and ensure orchestrator code is replay-safe (side-effect free during rehydration). Implement retry policies per activity with exponential backoff and demonstrate compensating actions for failures after persist (e.g., emit a synthetic cancellation event) while maintaining idempotency keys. Provide a deterministic timer event to model waiting for external signals and a timeout path that posts a “pending review” outcome. Outputs: compact visualized histories for three orders (success, retried success, compensated failure), orchestration latency stats, and idempotency validation (replaying history yields identical state). Include a small doc digest on why orchestrator code must be deterministic and how event-sourced state enables reliable recovery. Acceptance: replays never duplicate side effects; retries follow policy; compensation occurs exactly once; timers awaken the orchestrator deterministically. No real cloud calls—just faithful control-flow semantics.""",

    """Design a minimal Azure Monitor–style metric store with near-real-time ingestion, downsampling, and alert evaluation. Generate deterministic metrics (CPU, memory, errorRate) for five synthetic services. Ingest high-resolution points (e.g., 10-second) into an in-memory store, enforce a retention policy, and produce rollups (1-minute, 5-minute) via fixed aggregators (avg, p95, max). Implement three alert rules: (1) static threshold, (2) rate-of-change, and (3) rolling percentile breach, each with evaluation periods and cooldowns. Add a simple alert state machine (OK→ALERTING→ACKED→OK) and produce notifications with context (current value, threshold, contributing series). Outputs: raw and rolled-up metric counts, latency from ingestion to evaluation, alert timelines, and example notifications. Provide a doc digest discussing the tradeoffs between push vs pull evaluation, downsampling bias, and choosing stable aggregation windows. Acceptance: alerts fire deterministically under seeded spikes; cooldowns prevent alert flapping; rollups approximate raw signals while improving evaluation efficiency. Expose knobs for retention and aggregator choice to observe alert sensitivity and cost implications.""",

    """Model Azure Front Door/CDN caching behavior for API and asset routes with signed URL enforcement. Define routes: /api/* (mostly uncacheable) and /assets/* (cacheable with versioned fingerprints). Implement cache policy: vary by method, essential headers, and query keys; enforce TTLs and soft/hard expirations with background refresh (stale-while-revalidate) for assets. Add signed URL validation for private asset links using HMAC on path+expiry; expired or tampered links are rejected. Simulate traffic with a fixed seed: a blend of cacheable asset requests and uncacheable API calls. Outputs: hit/miss ratios over time, origin load reduction, average asset latency improvement with SWR, and a sample rejected link explanation (signature mismatch vs expired). Include a short operational digest on why excessive Vary keys destroy cacheability and how fingerprinted assets permit long TTLs without staleness risk. Acceptance: cache hit rate rises with repeated asset access; invalid signatures never serve; API routes remain uncacheable by policy but benefit from connection reuse assumptions. Keep all cryptography deterministic via fixed keys for repeatability.""",

    """Create a blue/green rollout simulator for containerized services similar to container apps behind a weighted traffic splitter. Represent two revisions (blue=current, green=candidate) with independent error/latency distributions. Implement a controller that shifts weight in steps based on SLO guardrails (p95 latency and error rate), with automatic rollback if green breaches thresholds. Collect per-revision metrics, compute weighted end-to-end SLOs, and emit decision logs explaining each weight change (promote, hold, rollback) with the exact metric deltas that triggered it. Add a small canary mode where 1% of traffic is mirrored (shadowed) to green for early signal collection without user impact; store shadow results separately and compare against live once promotion begins. Outputs: weight timeline, per-revision SLOs, breach events, and final rollout verdict. Provide a brief operations note on confidence intervals for short windows and the risk of noisy metrics making rollouts oscillate. Acceptance: under seeded good behavior, rollout reaches 100% green; under seeded regressions, controller halts or rolls back with documented reasons. Ensure behavior is reproducible and parameters (window length, thresholds, step size) are tunable at runtime.""",

    """Implement a configuration-driven ETL planner that compiles high-level transformations into an execution graph with explicit data contracts. Define a declarative spec for synthetic orders and customers: joins by key, computed columns (e.g., order value), and simple aggregations (daily totals). Validate the spec (required keys, allowed functions, non-circular dependencies) and compile to a directed acyclic graph of steps with clear contracts: each step declares input schema, output schema, and invariants (e.g., non-null keys). Execute with deterministic synthetic inputs and produce lineage metadata: for each output field, list upstream sources and transformations. Outputs: compiled graph (nodes/edges), contract validation results, lineage for three selected outputs, and a run summary (rows processed, constraint violations, elapsed). Add a doc digest on why explicit contracts make refactors safer and how schema drift surfaces early. Acceptance: changing a column name in the spec fails fast with a contract error; disabling a step updates downstream lineage; re-running with the same seed yields identical outputs. Keep execution in memory, emphasize engineering discipline over data volume.""",

    """Compose a minimal role-based access control (RBAC) model for service-to-service calls across three synthetic microservices: orders, billing, and inventory. Define principals (services), roles (reader, writer, admin), and permissions (endpoint + method). Implement policy evaluation: on each request, assert a principal’s role binding and check permission against the policy table; return deterministic deny reasons (missing role, missing permission, expired binding). Add time-boxed tokens with scopes and a tiny key rotation routine that invalidates old signing keys and issues new ones; validate tokens (signature, expiry, scope) before evaluating role policy. Generate a deterministic traffic mix including valid and invalid tokens, and report allowed vs denied counts and the top deny reasons. Outputs: policy table, example tokens (header/payload only), evaluation logs for five sample requests, and a compliance summary that highlights least-privilege gaps (e.g., admins used for read-only paths). Include a doc digest on separating authentication (token validity) from authorization (role/permission checks). Acceptance: expired tokens are always rejected; principals without explicit permissions are denied by default; rotating keys invalidates old tokens immediately while allowing new issuance. All behavior remains deterministic with fixed keys and seeds.""",

    """Create a proactive throttling and shed-load guard for a synthetic read-heavy API with occasional write bursts. Track moving averages for requests per second and concurrent in-flight work; define target ceilings per route class (read/write). When pressure exceeds targets, apply progressive controls: (1) quick-fail low-priority reads with Retry-After hints, (2) degrade response detail (omit expensive fields) for medium priority, and (3) reserve capacity for writes. Record every decision with a structured reason (metric, threshold, route, policy step) and compute end-to-end p50/p95 and tail error rates. Simulate bursty traffic with a fixed seed, including thundering herd scenarios after cache invalidations. Outputs: admitted vs rejected by route, latency distributions before/after shedding, and three example degraded responses annotated with decisions taken. Provide a doc digest on fairness (route weights), the difference between client- vs server-enforced throttles, and how Retry-After enables well-behaved clients. Acceptance: under burst, the guard maintains write SLOs while gracefully degrading reads; decisions are deterministic and explainable; removing the guard increases tail latencies and error rates in a repeatable way. Keep all knobs configurable and observable at runtime.""",

    """Implement a simple Distributed Lock Manager (DLM) using Azure Cache for Redis semantics. Define a resource name, a lock duration (TTL), and a unique client ID. Simulate three competing workers attempting to acquire the same lock using a simple SETNX (SET if Not eXists) logic. Implement a simple, deterministic retry logic on failure. Acceptance: Only one worker holds the lock at any given time; a worker failing to acquire the lock after N retries gives up; a worker must explicitly release the lock. Outputs: Lock acquisition/release event log (worker ID, time, duration), successful lock counts, and a doc digest on why SETNX/EX is the basic requirement for distributed locking and the risk of a crashing worker. """,

    """Model Azure Blob Storage tiering policies for cost optimization. Given synthetic blob metadata (path, size, lastModified), define a policy JSON (e.g., 'Move /logs/* to Cool after 30 days', 'Move /archives/* to Archive after 90 days'). Implement an engine that reads the metadata and outputs a list of proposed tier transitions ([blob_path, current_tier, new_tier, reason]). Acceptance: Engine must process rules in defined order; a blob is only proposed for the single most cost-effective tier; simulate one month of data evolution and show the resulting tier assignments. Outputs: Policy JSON, transition list, and a doc digest on the differences between Hot, Cool, and Archive tiers and their primary cost factors (storage vs access). """,

    """Simulate a cross-region Azure Service Bus failover. Model a primary queue and a secondary (passive) queue. Generate a continuous stream of seeded messages. Implement a controller that, upon a simulated failure of the primary, switches the consumer's connection to the secondary. Crucially, before switching, the system must read and drain any messages left in the primary's Dead-Letter Queue (DLQ). Acceptance: Consumer maintains message processing order despite the failover; demonstrate zero message loss during a controlled failover; after failover, traffic is routed to the secondary. Outputs: Failover timeline (event, reason, new state), total processed message count, and a doc digest on active/passive failover and the importance of DLQ draining. """,

    """Build an API endpoint that ensures idempotency using a simple ETag check (like Cosmos DB or Azure Storage). Define a resource with fields: id, version, and etag (a simple hash). Implement PUT /resource/{id} that accepts an optional If-Match header. If the header matches the current ETag, update the resource and generate a new ETag; otherwise, return a 412 Precondition Failed. Acceptance: Sending the same payload and ETag twice results in one successful update and one 412 error; a concurrent update attempt fails with 412 for the second caller. Outputs: API spec, sample success/failure response with ETag headers, and a doc digest on how ETags are used for optimistic concurrency control. """,

    """Design an Azure CDN cache invalidation service. Define an in-memory cache for content by URL with a TTL. Implement a purge service that accepts a list of URLs and invalidates the cache entries. Model two purge types: Full Purge (path only, ignoring query strings) and Selective Purge (path + query string). Track cache hit/miss ratios before and after purges. Acceptance: Purging asset.png also invalidates asset.png?v=1; purging asset.png?v=2 only invalidates that specific entry; demonstrate a clear increase in cache misses immediately after a purge. Outputs: Cache state before/after purge, hit/miss metrics, and a doc digest on the latency implications of purges and the concept of 'cache busting' with versioned URLs. """,

    """Create a lightweight engine to simulate an Azure Policy evaluation. Define a resource (e.g., Azure Storage Account) and a set of policy rules (e.g., 'Must have a specific tag', 'Public access must be disabled'). Implement an evaluation function that takes a resource configuration and a policy rule set, and outputs a compliance verdict (Compliant/Non-Compliant) with a detailed reason. Add a proposed remediation action. Acceptance: A non-compliant resource configuration yields a specific failure reason; applying the proposed remediation results in a compliant configuration; show the difference between an Audit and a Deny policy effect. Outputs: Policy rule set, sample resource verdict log, and a doc digest on the difference between Audit, Deny, and Modify policy effects. """,

    """Engineer a module to enforce and report on resource tagging for cost allocation. Define a set of required tags (Environment, CostCenter). Process a list of synthetic resources (each with ID, type, and an arbitrary tag set). Implement a validation step for required tags and case sensitivity. Based on valid tags, project the total monthly cost, broken down by CostCenter. Acceptance: Resources with missing or improperly cased tags are flagged; the total cost is accurately aggregated per cost center; demonstrate how a mis-tagged resource is excluded from the cost report. Outputs: Validation report, cost allocation table by CostCenter, and a doc digest on using tags versus resource groups for cost management. """,

    """Model the cold start behavior of Azure Functions under varied load. Define a deterministic request generator. Simulate a pool of containers that scale to zero after a configurable idle time. Requests to a cold container incur a high, variable setup latency (cold_start_time). Track request latencies and compute p99 and average latency under burst and sustained load. Acceptance: Latency p99 spikes significantly during bursts after idle periods; a sustained low-level load prevents cold starts; show the impact of the idle timeout. Outputs: Time series of active containers, request latency p99/p50 over time, and a doc digest on cold start mitigation techniques (minimum instances, premium plans). """,

    """Simulate Azure Private Link and Service Endpoint access control. Define a VNet with three subnets, an Azure Storage Account (Service Endpoint enabled), and an Azure Key Vault (Private Link enabled). Define synthetic clients in different subnets. Implement a routing decision function to determine if a client is allowed to access the storage account and key vault. Acceptance: Clients in the Service Endpoint subnet can access the Storage Account; clients connecting to the Key Vault's private IP succeed; show how a client in a non-configured subnet is denied access. Outputs: Access matrix (client, target, allowed/denied, reason), and a doc digest on the security and networking benefits of Private Link vs Service Endpoints. """,

    """Model a simple Geo-Replication with Last Write Wins (LWW) conflict resolution (like Cosmos DB multi-master). Simulate two regions, A and B. Generate concurrent, conflicting writes to the same document ID in both regions. Implement an LWW resolution based on a logical timestamp. Ensure all replicas converge to the same final state. Track the number of conflicts. Acceptance: The document converges to the version with the highest timestamp; the final state is identical in both regions after convergence; show how the document version/eTag changes after resolution. Outputs: Write history log (region, ID, timestamp, new value), final document state, and a doc digest on the LWW policy and the concept of eventual consistency. """,

    """Design a resolver for a simplified IaC (Infrastructure as Code) specification (like Bicep/Terraform). Define resources that explicitly or implicitly depend on others. Build a dependency graph (DAG) and implement a topological sort to produce the correct, parallelizable deployment order. Flag and reject circular dependencies. Acceptance: Subnet creation is ordered after its VNet; the output order is guaranteed to deploy dependent resources last; a manually injected circular dependency is immediately detected. Outputs: Input IaC spec, the resulting DAG (as a data structure), the final deployment order, and a doc digest on the necessity of topological sorting for declarative infrastructure. """,

    """Implement a module to validate a simple Azure Active Directory (AAD) JWT token. Define a fixed public key for signature verification. Implement steps: 1) Signature validation, 2) Expiry/Not-Before time checks, 3) Audience check, and 4) Issuer check. If valid, parse the 'roles' claim. If invalid, provide a precise denial reason. Acceptance: An expired token is rejected with an expiry error; a token with the wrong audience is rejected; valid tokens are accepted and roles extracted. Outputs: Sample valid/invalid JWTs, validation outcome log, and a doc digest on the role of the 'aud' and 'iss' claims in token security. """,

    """Build a deterministic, in-memory scanner that simulates a Data Loss Prevention (DLP) check on text data. Define a simple regex for sensitive information (e.g., email addresses, fake credit card numbers). Implement a scoring function that computes a risk score per document based on the number of matches. Flag documents above a threshold. Acceptance: Documents with clear matches are flagged; the risk score accurately reflects the concentration of sensitive data; show how the threshold controls the blocking level. Outputs: Document ID, risk score, list of matched patterns, and a doc digest on the limitations of regex-based DLP and the concept of false positives. """,

    """Model an asynchronous request-response pattern using an in-memory queue (simulating Azure Storage Queue). Define a Requestor that puts a message on an input queue with a correlation ID and a reply address. A Worker processes the message and writes the result to a shared store. Implement a polling mechanism for the Requestor to retrieve the final result, including a configurable timeout. Acceptance: The API call immediately returns an accepted status; the final result is eventually retrieved using the correlation ID; a timeout path is correctly executed. Outputs: Request timeline (submission, processing, retrieval), average wait time, and a doc digest on the benefits of asynchronous patterns for long-running operations. """,

    """Simulate an Azure Event Grid Pub/Sub system, focusing on event filtering. Define an event schema (source, eventType, data.status). Implement subscriber registration that allows filtering based on: 1) Prefix (e.g., eventType starts with 'order.'), 2) Suffix (e.g., eventType ends with '.completed'), and 3) Advanced (e.g., data.status = 'ERROR'). Generate a deterministic stream of events and route them only to matching subscribers. Acceptance: Events are only delivered if all registered filters are matched; the system handles a lack of matching subscribers gracefully; a complex filter with multiple rules functions correctly. Outputs: Event stream, per-subscriber delivery log, and a doc digest on why filtering at the broker is preferred over filtering at the subscriber. """,

    """Model an Azure Load Balancer with two backend instances. Implement a deterministic Health Probe that checks an endpoint every N seconds; an instance is marked unhealthy after M consecutive failures. The load balancer must use a simple round-robin policy *only* for healthy instances. Introduce a controlled, transient failure on one instance. Acceptance: Requests are only routed to healthy instances; the load balancer accurately detects and removes the failed instance from rotation; after recovery, the instance is automatically added back. Outputs: Health status timeline per instance, request routing log, and a doc digest on the necessity of the 'unhealthy threshold' (M). """,

    """Build a pipeline that reads synthetic JSON records (like a Data Lake landing zone) and infers a consolidated schema (union of all fields with resolved types). Implement a validation step that uses the inferred schema to check new incoming records for type consistency and missing required fields. Acceptance: The inferred schema correctly identifies the superset of all fields; new records that violate the inferred type are flagged; demonstrate how the system handles null values when inferring required/optional status. Outputs: Inferred canonical schema, validation report for incoming batches, and a doc digest on schema-on-read vs. schema-on-write. """,

    """Model a CI/CD pipeline promotion process with approval gates. Define three environments (Dev, Staging, Prod). Promotion to Staging is automatic; promotion to Prod requires a deterministic 'Staging Metrics SLO Check' (simulated threshold check) and a final 'Human Approval' (simulated external signal). Implement a state machine for an artifact that progresses through environments. Acceptance: The artifact stalls at the correct gates waiting for signals; a failed SLO check automatically blocks promotion to Prod; the system provides a clear audit trail for every state transition. Outputs: Artifact promotion history, audit log, and a doc digest on the importance of immutable artifacts and using promotion gates. """,

    """Engineer a throttling mechanism that enforces a Burst Rate Limit (e.g., 100 requests per second) and a Lease Quota (e.g., only 5 concurrent requests can hold a 'processing lease'). Implement a request handler that attempts to acquire both a rate-limit token and a lease. If either fails, the request is immediately rejected. Use a fixed seed to generate bursty traffic. Acceptance: The system never exceeds the configured RPS or the concurrent lease limit; rejected requests receive a deterministic denial reason; show the difference in behavior when only the burst limit is hit vs. only the lease quota. Outputs: Admitted vs. rejected counts by reason, time-series of concurrent leases held, and a doc digest on the difference between rate limiting and concurrency limiting. """,

    """Simulate a distributed transaction across three synthetic services (A -> B -> C). Implement logic to generate and propagate a Trace ID and a simple Parent/Child Span ID (like OpenTelemetry). Each service must record its start/end time and a Trace Context. Compute the end-to-end latency and the latency of each individual span. Introduce a controlled, transient delay in Service B. Acceptance: All spans for a single transaction share the same Trace ID; the parent-child relationship of spans is preserved; the total end-to-end latency is accurately calculated. Outputs: Trace log with hierarchical structure, end-to-end latency, and a doc digest on the role of the Trace ID and Span ID in root cause analysis. """,

    """Model an Azure Event Hubs consumer group's behavior in managing partition offsets and checkpointing. Define 4 partitions and a consumer group with 2 instances. Consumers read batches of events and must periodically checkpoint their last processed offset *atomically* per partition. Simulate a consumer failure and restart, demonstrating recovery from the last committed checkpoint. Acceptance: On restart, the consumer resumes reading from the checkpointed offset; different consumers checkpoint independently for their owned partitions; ensure bounded reprocessing. Outputs: Partition ownership map, checkpoint log (partition, offset), restart recovery summary, and a doc digest on why checkpointing granularity matters for recovery speed. """,

    """Design a model for an SQL Connection Pool with a fixed maximum size. Implement a connection request/release mechanism. Implement a request queuing system when the pool is full, with a configurable Wait Timeout. If a request waits too long, it should fail fast. Simulate a high-load scenario where requests exceed pool capacity. Acceptance: The pool size never exceeds the maximum; requests fail after the wait timeout with a specific reason; demonstrate how connection reuse is prioritized. Outputs: Connection pool utilization time-series, average wait time, timeout failure count, and a doc digest on the risks of connection leaks and the necessity of pool limits. """,

    """Create a centralized configuration client that models Azure App Configuration with dynamic updates. Define three configuration values, one of which is a Feature Flag. The client must fetch config and cache it locally with a TTL. Implement a background refresh that updates the cache without blocking read operations. Use a Sentinel Key (a special key) to efficiently check if *any* configuration value has changed. Acceptance: The client only fetches new config after the TTL expires or the Sentinel Key is updated; a read operation always uses the currently cached value; toggling the feature flag is reflected within the TTL. Outputs: Config fetch log, feature flag status over time, cache hit/miss ratio, and a doc digest on the benefits of the Sentinel Key pattern for efficient configuration polling. """,

    """Model the state transitions for a simplified SAML or OIDC Single Sign-On (SSO) flow. Define the essential steps: Unauthenticated, Redirect to IdP, Receive Assertion/Token, Validate and Create Session, Authenticated. Implement a deterministic failure path for invalid tokens or expired requests. Track the end-to-end latency of the SSO flow. Acceptance: The state machine correctly transitions through success and failure paths; an invalid token results in a denial before a session is created; show how a signed request parameter prevents CSRF. Outputs: SSO flow timeline, final session status, and a doc digest on the high-level differences between SAML and OIDC. """,

    """Design a utility that generates virtual metadata for a Data Lake structure (like Azure Synapse or Databricks). Given a base path (/data/events) and a partition scheme (/year={YYYY}/month={MM}), and a date range, the tool must generate the list of *expected* partition paths. Implement a Partition Projection logic that can compute a path for a given query (e.g., WHERE year = 2025 AND month = 09). Acceptance: The generated path list is deterministic for a fixed date range; a query constrained on date only generates a small, matching subset of paths. Outputs: Generated path list, query-to-path resolution log, and a doc digest on the performance benefits of partition pruning in data lakes. """,

    """Simulate an API Gateway (Azure API Management) that performs header manipulation and simple payload transformation. Define two rules: 1) Request Inbound: Remove sensitive headers (Authorization), inject a correlation ID, and transform a simple JSON payload to a new format. 2) Response Outbound: Inject a rate limit header, and transform the backend's error response into a standardized client error envelope. Acceptance: The backend receives the transformed, sanitized request; the client receives the standardized, decorated response; show that a missing required client header results in an early gateway rejection. Outputs: Sample inbound request, transformed backend request, and final client response, along with a doc digest on the security benefits of payload transformation at the gateway layer. """,

    """Implement a mechanism for automatically reprocessing messages from a Dead-Letter Queue (DLQ). Define a main queue consumer that, on failure, moves the message to the DLQ. Implement a separate DLQ Monitor that periodically polls the DLQ. Messages are only redelivered to the main queue if their retry count is below a threshold and they have passed a Backoff Delay (e.g., 5 minutes). Acceptance: Messages are not immediately redelivered; a message with too many failures is permanently moved to a Permanent Failure Queue; show the delay enforced by the backoff mechanism. Outputs: Message retry history (attempt, time, status), DLQ size over time, and a doc digest on the necessity of backoff in DLQ reprocessing. """,

    """Model the deployment process for an Azure App Service using Blue/Green slots (Production and Staging). Implement a deterministic Slot Swap operation with a critical Warm-up Phase. During the warm-up, traffic is mirrored (but not served to users) until a health check endpoint returns success. Track the time spent in the warm-up phase. Acceptance: The swap only completes after the Staging slot's health check is successful; a failed warm-up results in an automatic roll-back; show that production traffic is unaffected during the warm-up. Outputs: Slot state timeline, warm-up duration, and a doc digest on why the warm-up step is vital for zero-downtime deployments. """,

    """Build an engine to manage time-series data (like Azure Monitor). Ingest high-resolution points (e.g., CPU utilization every 10 seconds). Implement a rollup process that aggregates these points into lower-resolution buckets (1-minute and 1-hour), using configurable functions (average, max). Enforce a simple retention policy. Acceptance: Queries for a 1-hour window return the high-resolution data within the retention period and the aggregated data otherwise; the rollup calculations are accurate. Outputs: Ingestion count, rollup counts by resolution, and a doc digest on the storage/performance trade-offs of rollups. """,

    """Implement an Access Control List (ACL) evaluation for a hierarchical file system, similar to Azure Data Lake Storage Gen2's POSIX-like permissions. Define principals (users/groups) and permissions (Read/Write/Execute). Implement an access check function that recursively evaluates permissions, where permissions are inherited from the parent directory unless explicitly overridden. Acceptance: A user denied on a folder is also denied on all children unless explicitly granted; show how the Execute permission is necessary for directory traversal. Outputs: Folder structure and ACLs, access test matrix (user, path, action, allowed/denied, reason), and a doc digest on the difference between inherited and explicit permissions. """,

    """Simulate a custom policy engine to enforce data residency requirements. Define synthetic data objects, each tagged with a Geography (e.g., 'EU', 'US'). Define a policy that restricts processing functions to run only in specific geographies. Implement a dispatcher that accepts a data object and a function, and either executes it or denies it with a clear residency violation reason. Acceptance: EU data is blocked from being processed by a US-only function; US data is successfully processed by a US- or Global-enabled function; demonstrate how a mis-tagged piece of data leads to a policy failure. Outputs: Policy configuration, processing attempt log (data ID, function, result, violation reason), and a doc digest on the architectural impact of data residency. """,

    """Model a simplified Two-Phase Commit (2PC) transaction coordinator for three synthetic microservices: Orders, Inventory, and Payment. Each service implements a prepare and a commit/rollback endpoint. The coordinator initiates the prepare phase and, if all services vote 'ok', proceeds to 'commit'; otherwise, it issues a 'rollback' to all. Acceptance: A successful transaction commits atomically across all three services; a single service failure causes all three to roll back; show the two distinct phases of the protocol. Outputs: Transaction log (phase, service, vote, action), final state of all services, and a doc digest on the core principle of 2PC. """,

    """Design a rule engine to simulate an Azure WAF (Web Application Firewall). Define three simple rule types: 1) Signature Match (e.g., simple SQL injection pattern in query string), 2) Geo-Blocking (deny requests from a specific country), and 3) Rate Limiting (block an IP after N requests in M seconds). Implement a request inspection function that applies all rules sequentially and returns the final action (Allow, Block, Log). Acceptance: A request with a simulated SQL injection pattern is blocked; a request from a blocked IP range is blocked; a burst of traffic from a single IP is throttled. Outputs: WAF rule set, request log with final action and triggering rule, and a doc digest on the primary function of a WAF. """,

    """Engineer a system to generate and validate a tamper-proof Audit Log. Each log entry must include a Content Hash (of its payload) and a Chain Hash (hash of the previous entry's entire content). Implement a deterministic Integrity Checker that can validate the entire chain from end to start. Acceptance: Modifying a single log entry causes the integrity check to fail at that point and all subsequent entries; appending a new, valid entry does not invalidate the existing chain; the system can quickly pinpoint the location of the tampering. Outputs: Sample audit log (with all hashes), integrity check verdict, and a doc digest on the use of cryptographic chaining for immutability. """,

    """Model a simple Service Discovery client that resolves logical service names (e.g., 'api.payments.internal') to physical endpoint URLs. Use a pluggable backend (simulated) that provides a list of healthy endpoints with a version number and a DNS TTL. The client must cache the resolution and only refresh when the TTL expires. Implement a basic client-side Load Balancing (e.g., random selection) across available, healthy endpoints. Acceptance: The client uses the cached value until the TTL expires; after TTL expiry, the client fetches the new version; a failed endpoint is removed from the load balancing pool. Outputs: Resolution request log (service name, cached/fresh, result), endpoint health status, and a doc digest on the benefits of client-side service discovery. """
    ]

   

    def generate_curriculum(self):
        return (
            self.generate_easy_tasks()
            + self.generate_medium_tasks()
            + self.generate_medium_hard_tasks()
            + self.generate_hard_tasks()
        )
